    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" subtype="primary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#JP" source="http://zotero.org/groups/382445/items/F2GG87EQ">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name>Σιλανός</name></persName> <space unit="character" extent="unknown"/> <persName type="attested"><name>Σιλανός</name></persName>
                    <lb n="2"/> ἥρωες ἀγαθοί
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp><app><note>Text of Giustolisi as reported in SEG</note></app></listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p><!--translation(s) - add @xml:lang for 'en' or 'it' to div--></p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Giustolisi proposed that it was a dedication to or invovation of the divinity Silenos, but Manganaro, and Moretti (comm in SEG) instead suggest that it is a funerary aedicola for two men called Silenos, perhaps father and son, with the designation as heroes agathoi, as is common in the later Hellenistic period.</p>
            </div>
